300 720 1693 (The purpose of this message is to respond to the statements made about the "name leakage" problem) 1693 SB
300 770 1770 (attributed to the "inclusion" compilation model.  In this message I will illustrate why the "name leakage") 1770 SB
300 820 1752 (issue has been a fact of life in C++ far longer than templates have been around, and why the  separation) 1752 SB
300 870 1704 (model actually suffers from far more serious "name leakage" problems. A "feature"  of the separation) 1704 SB
300 920 1073 (model actually permits names to leak between translation units.) 1073 SB
32 0 0 58 58 0 0 0 53 /Helvetica-Bold /font13 ANSIFont font
300 1070 64 (2. ) 78 SB
378 1070 1351 (Why the \223name leakage\224 problem is a red herring) 1351 SB
32 0 0 42 42 0 0 0 38 /Times-Roman /font32 ANSIFont font
300 1152 1687 (In the inclusion model, the "name leakage" that occurs is nothing more than the same issue that has) 1687 SB
300 1202 1721 (affected class definitions and inline function definitions in header files as long as C++ has existed.  In) 1721 SB
300 1252 1642 (other words, code in header files that is included in multiple files can mean different things if the) 1642 SB
300 1302 1090 (declarations that precede that code vary from one file to another.) 1090 SB
300 1402 1781 (The following is basically the name leakage example from Bjarne's reflector posting, that I've modified to) 1781 SB
300 1452 1779 (include the definition and use of my_class.  I've also modified it so that use2.c includes sum.h, and sum.h) 1779 SB
300 1502 1106 (includes sum.c as would typically be done in the inclusion model.) 1106 SB
