300 1469 1736 (In this example, when using the separation model, there are either 6 or 8  different possible contexts in) 1736 SB
300 1519 588 (which f1\(char\) can be instantiated.) 588 SB
300 1619 160 (They are:) 160 SB
300 1719 151 (        f2.c) 151 SB
300 1769 151 (        f3.c) 151 SB
300 1819 260 (        f1.c + f2.c) 260 SB
300 1869 260 (        f1.c + f3.c) 260 SB
300 1919 369 (        f1.c + f2.c + f3.c) 369 SB
300 1969 369 (        f1.c + f3.c + f2.c) 369 SB
300 2019 260 (        f2.c + f3.c) 260 SB
300 2069 260 (        f3.c + f2.c) 260 SB
300 2169 1724 (The reason I say 6 or 8 is that it is possible that the context merging process is commutative \(e.g., that) 1724 SB
300 2219 1693 (f1+f2 is equivalent to f2+f1\).  Because the context merging process is unspecified, it is impossible to) 1693 SB
300 2269 356 (answer this question.) 356 SB
300 2369 1649 (The proliferation of instantiation contexts makes the already difficult process of trying to do ODR) 1649 SB
300 2419 1117 (checking even more expensive when the separation model is used.) 1117 SB
300 2519 1782 (Under the inclusion model, each template has, at most, one instantiation point for each translation unit in) 1782 SB
300 2569 1786 (which it is referenced.  In the separation model, on the other hand, the number of instantiation contexts is) 1786 SB
300 2619 1625 (dependent on the call graph of template based functions.  Because adding nodes has the effect of) 1625 SB
300 2669 1770 (multiplying the number of possible paths through the graph, it is very easy to have very large numbers of) 1770 SB
300 2719 1761 (possible instantiation contexts. For example, by adding one more template based call site for both f2 and) 1761 SB
300 2769 1751 (f3, the number of possible instantiation sites doubles from 8 to 16.  In real applications that make heavy) 1751 SB
300 2819 1790 (use of templatized data types and libraries like STL, the number of possible instantiation sites could easily) 1790 SB
300 2869 335 (reach the thousands) 335 SB
